**How this September's drought levels compare to years prior**
According to the U.S. Drought Monitor (USDM), this year's drought levels in Central Texas are significantly reduced compared to years prior. The USDM map, released every Thursday, uses six categories to determine drought severity, including normal, abnormally dry, moderate, severe, extreme, and exceptional. Historically, exceptional drought (D4) has led to widespread crop loss, tree mortality, and water sanitation concerns. In contrast, this September has seen little to no severity in Travis County. Looking back at recent years, three out of the past five years have been mostly drought, with 2023 being the outlier. Last year, 38.71% of the Austin/San Antonio area was under an exceptional drought, making it the second hottest and driest year on record.
