**70% of the Population Will Be Affected by Extreme Weather in the Next 20 Years**
According to a new study, approximately 1.5 billion people will suffer from extreme temperatures, rain, and winds in the next 20 years. The study warns that climate change will lead to more intense and frequent extreme weather events. For example, the combination of drought and heatwaves is causing more frequent and intense forest fires worldwide. In 2022, a severe heatwave in Pakistan was followed by unprecedented flooding, affecting millions of people. Brazil is also experiencing the effects of climate change, with the Rio Grande do Sul experiencing historic floods in the first half of the year and the rest of the country facing its worst drought in decades. The researchers state that heatwaves can cause heat stress, excess mortality in humans and livestock, stress on ecosystems, reduced agricultural productivity, and disruptions to energy cooling and transportation. Similarly, extreme precipitation can lead to flooding, damage to settlements, infrastructure, crops, and ecosystems, increased erosion, and reduced water quality.
